      devanagari: "उशन् ह वै वाजश्रवसः सर्ववेदसं ददौ ।\nतस्य ह नचिकेता नाम पुत्र आस ॥",
      transliteration: "uśan ha vai vājaśravasaḥ sarva-vedasaṁ dadau\ntasya ha naciketā nāma putra āsa",
      translation: "Desiring reward, Vajashravasa gave away all that he owned. He had a son named Nachiketa.",
      words: [{ "word": "uśan", "meaning": "desiring / wishing (for the fruits of the sacrifice)" }, { "word": "ha vai", "meaning": "indeed, so the story goes — the storyteller's opening" }, { "word": "vājaśravasaḥ", "meaning": "Vajashravasa — \"famed for food-gifts\"; the father" }, { "word": "sarva-vedasam dadau", "meaning": "gave away all his possessions / his whole wealth" }, { "word": "tasya ha naciketā nāma putra āsa", "meaning": "he had a son by the name Nachiketa" }],
      commentary: "One verse, and the trap is already set. A man performs the grandest of sacrifices — the kind where you give away everything you own — and the very first word of the Upanishad quietly tells you why he is doing it: uśan, \"desiring.\" Desiring the reward, the merit, the heaven that the ritual manuals promise. The gift is total on the outside and calculated on the inside. This is the oldest spiritual failure mode there is, and every tradition knows it: the outward form of renunciation performed as an investment strategy.\n\nWatch what the text does not do. It does not denounce Vajashravasa, does not call him a hypocrite, does not editorialize at all. It simply places one word — \"desiring\" — where an attentive reader will trip over it, and then introduces the person who will trip over it hardest: tasya ha naciketā nāma putra āsa. He had a son. The whole Upanishad hangs on that sentence. Institutions do not usually reform themselves; they are questioned by someone young enough to still see the gap between what is said and what is done. Nachiketa is about to watch the \"gift of everything\" walk past him — old cows, dry cows, cows that will never give milk again — and do the arithmetic a child does honestly: what merit can come from giving away what costs you nothing?\n\nFor us, the verse is a mirror before it is a story. Everyone has a Vajashravasa mode: generosity that quietly keeps receipts, work offered \"selflessly\" with one eye on the recognition, spiritual practice done for the optics of it. The Isha Upanishad told us to enjoy through letting go; Katha opens by showing the counterfeit version — letting go as a purchase. The question the boy is about to ask his father — \"to whom will you give me?\" — is the question this whole season puts to us: when you give, who is doing the giving, and what is it actually for?"
